`crates/ctx-verify/src` is the whole `ctx-verify` binary: a broker that runs cargo/clippy/script checks and emits one capped, deterministic JSON report (same schema family as the spec-audit tool). Depending on this crate means depending on `ctx_verify::cli::run` and the `model::Report`/`CheckReport` JSON contract; nothing else here is public surface.

The call chain is strict: `main.rs` (argv pre-scan for `--contract`, exit-code convention, writer plumbing) → `cli.rs` (clap parsing, terse/JSON rendering, the `CONTRACT` string synced with CLAUDE.md/README.md) → `checks.rs` (the fixed `SPECS` catalog, `run_selected` orchestration) → `runner.rs` (the sole process-spawning boundary, `Runner` trait). `parse.rs` turns each tool's raw output into `model::Diagnostic`, and `model.rs` defines the capped/truncated report shape with hand-written `Serialize` impls; `error.rs` holds the one `CheckError` enum threaded through `runner`/`checks`/`cli`.

Shared contracts an editor must respect: `checks.rs`'s parser choice (`compiler_parser`, `script_parser`, `test_parser`, `parse_fmt`) must match the actual tool output format — changing a script's stdout convention or cargo's JSON schema breaks parsing silently (malformed lines are dropped, not errored). `model::Diagnostic`'s field shape is depended on by both `parse.rs` and `checks.rs`'s truncation logic (`max` diagnostics, `truncated` count) — never silently drop excess diagnostics without recording the count. `CheckError` variants are matched at both `runner.rs` call sites and `checks.rs`/`cli.rs` error handling; adding a variant means updating all match sites. Adding a new check type requires touching `checks.rs` + `parse.rs` + `model.rs` together, per `lib.rs`'s explicit layering note — never call `runner` directly from `cli`.

Cross-cutting invariants: `Status::Errored` always outranks `Fail` in `Report::new`; `fmt` is the only mutating check (applies formatting rather than reporting); output only ever goes through explicit writer handles, never `println!`, so `cli::run` stays testable with in-memory buffers.